## 4. Data ingestion

### 4.1 Log sample

Example of raw log lines used in the lab:

```text
Apr 21 02:13:45 lab-host sshd[1245]: Failed password for invalid user admin from 192.168.1.45 port 53422 ssh2
Apr 21 02:13:48 lab-host sshd[1247]: Failed password for invalid user admin from 192.168.1.45 port 53423 ssh2
Apr 21 02:14:02 lab-host sshd[1250]: Accepted password for melissa from 10.0.0.15 port 50210 ssh2
ngestion steps (high level)
Configured a new Splunk data input for Linux auth logs.

Verified events were indexed under index=auth_logs.

Confirmed correct sourcetype=linux_secure.

5. SPL queries
5.1 Failed login attempts by source IP
spl
index=auth_logs sourcetype=linux_secure "Failed password"
| stats count AS failed_attempts by src_ip, user
| sort - failed_attempts
Purpose: Identify IPs generating high volumes of failed logins.

5.2 Brute‑force behavior over time
spl
index=auth_logs sourcetype=linux_secure "Failed password"
| bin _time span=5m
| stats count AS failed_attempts by _time, src_ip
| where failed_attempts > 10
| sort _time
Purpose: Detect bursts of failed logins that may indicate brute‑force attacks.

5.3 Successful logins after failures
spl
index=auth_logs sourcetype=linux_secure ("Failed password" OR "Accepted password")
| transaction src_ip user maxspan=30m
| search eventcount > 1 "Failed password" "Accepted password"
| table _time, src_ip, user, eventcount, duration
Purpose: Identify cases where an attacker may have eventually guessed a valid password.

