7. Findings
IP 192.168.1.45 generated 37 failed SSH login attempts within a short time window.

The majority of attempts targeted the admin account, which does not exist as a valid user on the system.

Activity occurred outside normal business hours (02:10–02:20 UTC).

Behavior is consistent with automated brute‑force scanning.

8. Indicators of compromise (IOCs)
Source IP: 192.168.1.45

Target account: admin

Time window: 02:10–02:20 UTC

Event type: SSH failed password attempts

9. Recommended response actions
Block or rate‑limit IP 192.168.1.45 at the firewall or edge device.

Disable or rename default/admin‑like accounts where possible.

Enforce strong password policies and MFA for remote access.

Add detection rules for:

High failed login counts per IP

High failed login counts per user

Successful login following multiple failures

10. Lessons learned
SIEM dashboards significantly reduce time‑to‑detect for brute‑force attempts.

Normalizing log data and using consistent sourcetype values is critical for reliable queries.

Visualizations help SOC analysts quickly prioritize which IPs and accounts to investigate.

